Copy constructor 2
A//
Number numA( 8 );
Number numB = numA;

//B
Number numA( 8 );
Number numC( numA ); 

In both cases numA is already created before numB.
Then numB is initialized.

A and B are operationally the same in terms of calling the copy constructor.

Copy Initialization (A): 
	The statement Number numB = numA; uses copy initialization. 
	This involves the copy constructor if the class Number has one defined. 
	Essentially, this syntax is equivalent to Number numB(numA); in terms of calling the copy constructor.

Direct Initialization (B): 
	The statement Number numC(numA); uses direct initialization. 
	This explicitly calls the copy constructor with numA as the argument.

In both cases, if you have defined a copy constructor for the class Number, 
it will be invoked to initialize numB and numC from numA. 
The end result is the same: both numB and numC will be created as copies of numA using the copy constructor.
